  "prompt": "Is J.K Rowling a pen name?",
  "response": "No, **J.K. Rowling** is not a pen name; it is the author's real name, with a slight modification. Joanne Rowling, the creator of the *Harry Potter* series, adopted \"J.K. Rowling\" as her professional name at the suggestion of her publisher, Bloomsbury. They believed a gender-neutral name would appeal more to young male readers, as they thought boys might be less inclined to read books written by a woman.\n\nRowling did not have a middle name, so she chose \"Kathleen\" (her grandmother's name) to represent the \"K\" in her initials. Thus, while \"J.K. Rowling\" is a variation of her given name, it is not a pen name in the traditional sense. She has also written under other pseudonyms, such as **Robert Galbraith** for her crime novels.",
